# Engineering Principles

These principles apply to all code, regardless of language, framework, or layer.

---

## Simplicity first

Write the simplest solution that correctly solves the current problem.

- Do not design for hypothetical futures
- Earn complexity before introducing it
- Every abstraction must isolate real instability or real variation
- If you cannot explain why a layer or pattern exists here, it probably should not

---

## Single reason to change

Each module, class, or function should have one reason to change.

- Group things that change together for the same reason
- Separate things that change for different reasons
- A class that mixes HTTP concerns, business rules, and persistence has too many reasons to change

---

## Naming communicates intent

Names are the primary documentation.

- Name variables, functions, and types for what they represent, not how they are implemented
- Avoid abbreviations, single-letter variables (except loop counters), and generic names (`Manager`, `Helper`, `Utils`, `Service` without qualification)
- A function named `Process` tells nothing; `PlaceOrder` or `ValidatePayment` communicates intent
- If a name needs a comment to explain it, the name is not good enough

---

## Functions do one thing

- Functions should be short, focused, and at a single level of abstraction
- Extract sub-steps into well-named helper functions rather than layering nested conditionals and logic in one place
- A function doing more than one thing is a candidate for extraction
- Side effects should be obvious from the name and placement

---

## Explicit over implicit

- Prefer explicit over convention-based, framework-magic behaviour in business-critical paths
- Hidden conventions that affect correctness create debugging cost
- Make dependencies, side effects, and failure modes visible

---

## Error handling is a first-class concern

- Handle expected failure paths explicitly; do not silently swallow exceptions
- Use structured result types (`Result<T>`) for expected failures; throw exceptions for truly unexpected failures
- Log errors with enough context to understand what failed and where
- Clean up resources explicitly; use `using` or `try/finally`

---

## Testability signals design quality

- If important business logic can only be tested through a full stack, it is probably in the wrong place
- Hard-to-test code usually indicates excessive coupling, misplaced responsibility, or hidden dependencies
- Prefer pure functions and injected dependencies for core logic
- Design for tests before writing them; do not retrofit testability as an afterthought

---

## Avoid duplication of knowledge

- Every business rule, algorithm, and significant decision should have a single, authoritative representation
- Duplication of code is sometimes acceptable; duplication of business logic is not
- If the same change must be made in multiple places to achieve a single business goal, that is a signal of design debt

---

## Observability is part of the design

- Production code should explain what it is doing at runtime
- Add structured logging for important operations, state changes, and failures
- Correlation identifiers should propagate through async and distributed flows
- Telemetry is not decoration — it is a reliability concern

---

## Least privilege and secure by default

- Functions, services, and APIs should request only the permissions they need
- Default to restrictive; require explicit opt-in for permissive behaviour
- Validate all inputs before use; never trust caller-supplied data without verification

---

## Do not suppress warnings silently

- Compiler warnings and linter findings represent real risk
- Fix warnings rather than suppressing them; if suppression is genuinely required, document why
- Treat security and null-safety warnings as blockers, not suggestions

---

## Dependency inversion

High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions.

- High-level policy depends on abstractions; low-level details implement them
- Use interfaces or abstract types to define contracts; inject implementations at runtime
- Avoid direct instantiation of concrete dependencies in business logic

---

## Open for extension, closed for modification

Add behaviour by extending, not by changing existing code.

- Use interfaces, abstract classes, or composition to allow new behaviour without editing stable code
- Prefer composition and strategy patterns over inheritance for variation
- When a change forces edits in many places, the design may be closed for extension

---

## Interface segregation

Clients should not depend on interfaces they do not use.

- Prefer small, focused interfaces over large, monolithic ones
- Split fat interfaces into role-specific contracts; clients depend only on what they need
- A class implementing many unrelated methods is a candidate for interface extraction

---

## Substitutability

Subtypes must be substitutable for their base types without breaking the application.

- Derived types must honour the contract of the base type; no surprising behaviour when substituted
- Overrides must not weaken preconditions or strengthen postconditions
- If substitution requires callers to check the concrete type, the hierarchy is broken

---

## Clean Architecture directive

Separate business logic from infrastructure and UI; dependencies point inward.

- Domain and application layers contain no framework or infrastructure types
- Outer layers (UI, persistence, transport) depend on inner layers; inner layers define interfaces
- Use interfaces to abstract external dependencies; keep domain logic pure and framework-agnostic

---

## Common anti-pattern signals

Raise these concerns when reviewing or designing:

- *God objects* — One class or module doing many unrelated things
- *Tight coupling* — Direct dependencies on concrete implementations instead of abstractions
- *Interface pollution* — Large interfaces forcing clients to depend on methods they never use
- *Mixed concerns* — HTTP, business rules, and persistence in the same place
- *Magic numbers* — Literals without named constants; business rules hidden in code
- *Testing implementation details* — Tests that assert internal state instead of observable behaviour

---

## Self-review before completion

Before a piece of work is considered done:

- [ ] Naming is clear and communicates intent
- [ ] Functions are focused and at a single level of abstraction
- [ ] Error paths are handled explicitly
- [ ] No hardcoded values that should be configurable
- [ ] No sensitive data in log output
- [ ] Test coverage exists for the important behaviour
- [ ] No commented-out code
- [ ] No `TODO` without a linked issue or ticket
